## Example 3 — Compare Distributions Using Mean and Standard Deviation

### Step 1: Track Team Timing Comparison

Twenty track members were timed on a one-mile run before their season began and again after their season was completed. Use the mean and standard deviation to compare the distributions. ![](media/image3.JPG)

Compare the means: A higher or lower mean indicates faster or slower average times.
Compare the standard deviations: A smaller standard deviation indicates more consistent times across team members.

### Step 2: Geometry Class Test Score Comparison

Mr. Williams recorded students' test scores of his two Geometry classes. Use the mean and standard deviation to compare the distributions. ![](media/image4.JPG)

Higher mean: Better average performance.
Smaller standard deviation: More consistent scores within that class.

